            <StackPanel x:Name="DrivingBox_StackPanel" Height="407" VerticalAlignment="Center" Margin="55,0">
                <Canvas x:Name="DrivingBox_Canvas" Height="394" Width="377" HorizontalAlignment="Left" VerticalAlignment="Center">
                    <Rectangle x:Name="Driving_Rectangle" Style="{DynamicResource ThemeControl_Element_Rectangle}" Width="377" Height="393" RadiusX="25" RadiusY="25" HorizontalAlignment="Center" VerticalAlignment="Center"/>
                    <TextBlock x:Name="Driving_Paragraph" Style="{DynamicResource ThemeControl_Invert_TextBlock}" IsHitTestVisible="False" FontFamily="Montserrat" FontStretch="Expanded" FontWeight="Medium" FontSize="13.5" Height="312" Canvas.Left="18" Canvas.Top="16" Width="341" TextWrapping="WrapWithOverflow"><Run Text="This application replicates the design language used in Tesla vehicles. "/><Run Text="The Vehicle is completely controlled by the screen, so the necessity for a responsive software, especially for a driving position, is important for these vehicles to operate and function. This also means that the vehicle needs to continue operation when self-driving, even if the screen were to fail; This is why Tesla separates the hardware and software between the screen and the self-driving system. This is where the design comes into safety and reliability, making sure the software is perfect, and the hardware is decentralized for each system; in case of failure. The less parts in a design, the better the hardware reliability is, and the more reliant a solution become on software. This applies to all technology solutions, and also explains why Tesla is undoubtedly more of a software oriented company over its vehicle manufacturing, not to say the manufacturing of self-driving vehicles isn't a daunting task by itself..."/><LineBreak/><Run/></TextBlock>
